    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Starr's Tactics Endanger Us All; Clients Would Clam Up</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bruce Neuman letter disputes June 9 editorial, which backed argument by Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth W Starr before US Supreme Court that attorney-client privilege should end with client's death; says privilege should be pierced only to prevent crime or when life is in jeopardy (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 9 editorial argues that attorney-client privilege should end with the client's death when prosecutors need information to convict criminals. But that would make it less likely that a client would give his lawyer information that might be used by a prosecutor. The privilege would be sacrificed for no reason.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 9 editorial argues that attorney-client privilege should end with the client's death when prosecutors need information to convict criminals. But that would make it less likely that a client would give his lawyer information that might be used by a prosecutor. The privilege would be sacrificed for no reason.</p>
        <p>The privilege should be pierced only to prevent a crime or when life is in jeopardy. Prosecutors have many other investigative methods that do not penetrate the client-lawyer relationship.</p>
        <p>BRUCE NEUMAN  East Hampton, N.Y., June 9, 1998</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
